Gritty, street feel to movie and filming technique.  Clich's abound.  Wife liked it, I thought it was ok.  I liked that it showed how violent parts of the border are and political winds blow one way or the other not necessarily the correct way.

Most of the actors I've never seen in starring roles before and it shows.  It was a decent Friday nite shoot en up.
Not original. Rehash of many other movies
Obviously a very low-budget film and very predictable with poor acting and unrealistic scenes. The story line was not even really good and nothing was realistic at all.
Only watched it for 10 mins before realizing (at least it seemed) it was a "B" movie and turned it off.
Being an immigrant myself I enjoyed the movie. It brought  back memories of what I had to do to get into this country. Now I'm an American citizen and life is so much easier.

The entire movie must have been filmed by a camera operator with advanced Parkinson's tremors.
Looks like a good description of what's happening down here.
This is a very interesting show on border problems and the people that live near the border. It seemed like a real event happening.

Background music is so loud it ruins the film at first; however, watched it until the end and justice was served in some small measure.  The problem of illegal immigration and the human suffering that is endured by the people just trying to make a life, is ever so sad.  They should be blaming their own country through for their poverty and using the energy they spend coming here to clean up the legal white collar crime that is robbing their citizens, who want to work for a living, of their chance to support their families.  Human greed always promotes human suffering.  Shame on a government who oppresses their people to the point that they would risk death for a better life.  For a low-budget film, this was not bad.  Too many of the world's elite turning their backs on the laborers who sweat to create their luxurious lifestyles.  Double shame on the lot of them.

Bad acting even though the script was OK but badly directed. Cameraman needs to go back to film school or maybe he won't ever get it.
Special effects were bad and timing was worse. Actors unable to convince anyone of anything. Everything was predictable, Etc...

I really tried to watch to the end but could not take it anymore after half the movie. I was hoping that some action would help save me from boredom but it was not meant to be.

"Protecting people who are breaking The United States laws" is worthy enough for viewing, as others have said here. P.S. I never finished it because I was tired. But I like how it talks about borderline personality disorger.
Puke. This movie really is terrible.  Horrible cinematography and ultra boring story line.
Too grainy. Bad color. Only watched a couple minutes.
weak film. I enjoy this type of film but this one was tired at best.
Striking look at the failures of Obama to keep America safe.  The conspiracy from the top to bring down the United States and set up terrorist attacks is chilling.

Extraordinarily timely and timeless; timely when it comes to our present situation with the dumb @#% in the whitehouse and the idiots in both houses of congress who, between themselves, don't have a backbone! Timeless due to the incessant rule of the seven deadly sins. Those who didn't get this are detined to repeat history because they are incapable of learning from it. The film was done well, the acting credible (most ordinary folks don't behave "over-the-top" like most of the "A-Listers" portray the common man!), and the situations probably understated but dead on the money whern it comes to our "order" to the south. This should be required watching for all of those in power in WDC and, if they don't get it, kick 'em out but don't wait for an election. A powerful picture!

This testosterone laden production sheds a little light on a different side of the illegal immigrant issue.  It shows us that these poor people are often sold out by their paid guides and robbed by bandits of their few meager possessions.  That piece of info is the only revelation in this mundane production.  The tale is of a group of Border Patrol agents that are assigned to control the escalating violence resulting from the immigrant robberies.  The agents have a few successes until the well organized bandits begin killing agents.  Of course politicians step in to save the agents by pulling the plug on everything and shutting the operation down. Surprise, surprise these guys made a promise and we wouldn't have a movie unless they tried to keep it.  The director gives you the "we're bad asses" shot so many times that it becomes almost comical....O.K.! We get it.  They flex and pose their way through "The gang that couldn't shoot straight" culminating with the obvious showdown with the bad guys at the end.  The story was fair, the acting and writing was passable, and the overall production was decent.  If you're home on a Saturday afternoon this ones isn't bad to watch between phone calls and loads of laundry.
Blah, kinda got old real quick with the guys posing and flexing thrir pecs.
Ok film with bad acting and lost plot line. Kind of chessy
